{"downloaded": true, "htmlmade": false, "id": "38635462", "source": "MED", "pmid": "38635462", "pmcid": "PMC11486837", "fullTextIdList": {"fullTextId": "PMC11486837"}, "doi": "10.1080/15265161.2024.2337418", "title": "Establishing and Defining an Approach to Climate Conscious Clinical Medical Ethics.", "authorString": "Hantel A, Marron JM, Abel GA.", "authorList": {"author": [{"fullName": "Hantel A", "firstName": "Andrew", "lastName": "Hantel", "initials": "A", "authorId": {"@type": "ORCID", "#text": "0000-0001-9612-3643"}, "authorAffiliationDetailsList": {"authorAffiliation": [{"affiliation": "Dana-Farber Cancer Institute."}, {"affiliation": "Harvard Medical School."}]}}, {"fullName": "Marron JM", "firstName": "Jonathan M", "lastName": "Marron", "initials": "JM", "authorId": {"@type": "ORCID", "#text": "0000-0001-8935-8524"}, "authorAffiliationDetailsList": {"authorAffiliation": [{"affiliation": "Dana-Farber Cancer Institute."}, {"affiliation": "Harvard Medical School."}]}}, {"fullName": "Abel GA", "firstName": "Gregory A", "lastName": "Abel", "initials": "GA", "authorId": {"@type": "ORCID", "#text": "0000-0003-1100-2813"}, "authorAffiliationDetailsList": {"authorAffiliation": [{"affiliation": "Dana-Farber Cancer Institute."}, {"affiliation": "Harvard Medical School."}]}}]}, "authorIdList": {"authorId": [{"@type": "ORCID", "#text": "0000-0001-8935-8524"}, {"@type": "ORCID", "#text": "0000-0001-9612-3643"}, {"@type": "ORCID", "#text": "0000-0003-1100-2813"}]}, "dataLinksTagsList": {"dataLinkstag": "altmetrics"}, "journalInfo": {"issue": "7", "volume": "25", "journalIssueId": "3974029", "dateOfPublication": "2025 Jul", "monthOfPublication": "7", "yearOfPublication": "2025", "printPublicationDate": "2025-07-01", "journal": {"title": "The American journal of bioethics : AJOB", "ISOAbbreviation": "Am J Bioeth", "medlineAbbreviation": "Am J Bioeth", "NLMid": "100898738", "ISSN": "1526-5161", "ESSN": "1536-0075"}}, "pubYear": "2025", "pageInfo": "8-21", "abstractText": "An anthropocentric scope for clinical medical ethics (CME) has largely separated this area of bioethics from environmental concerns. In this article, we first identify and reconcile the ethical issues imposed on CME by climate change including the dispersion of related causes and effects, the transdisciplinary and transhuman nature of climate change, and the historic divorce of CME from the environment. We then establish how several moral theories undergirding modern CME, such as virtue ethics, feminist ethics, and several theories of justice, promote both a flourishing of human medical practice and the environment. We conclude by defining an expanded the scope of CME as inclusive of not only patients, families, physicians, and other health professionals but other humans, non-humans, and their shared environment. We then apply this scope and theory to a widely used framework for applying CME, the Four Topics model, to construct a climate conscious approach to CME.", "affiliation": "Dana-Farber Cancer Institute.", "publicationStatus": "ppublish", "language": "eng", "pubModel": "Print-Electronic", "pubTypeList": {"pubType": ["research-article", "Journal Article"]}, "grantsList": {"grant": [{"grantId": "K08 CA273043", "agency": "the Greenwall Foundation under a Making-A-Difference Award; the National Cancer Institute of the National Institutes of Health", "orderIn": "0"}, {"grantId": "K08 CA273043", "agency": "NCI NIH HHS", "acronym": "CA", "orderIn": "0"}]}, "meshHeadingList": {"meshHeading": [{"majorTopic_YN": "N", "descriptorName": "Humans"}, {"majorTopic_YN": "N", "descriptorName": "Morals"}, {"majorTopic_YN": "N", "descriptorName": "Virtues"}, {"majorTopic_YN": "N", "descriptorName": "Social Justice"}, {"majorTopic_YN": "Y", "descriptorName": "Ethics, Clinical"}, {"majorTopic_YN": "N", "descriptorName": "Ethical Theory"}, {"majorTopic_YN": "Y", "descriptorName": "Ethics, Medical"}, {"majorTopic_YN": "N", "descriptorName": "Feminism"}, {"majorTopic_YN": "Y", "descri